00:08:25,250 --> 00:08:28,660
I mean, it's not like it's a huge threshold that he set up there.

168
00:08:28,660 --> 00:08:31,810
But I do think you want to have a formal part of that introduction where

169
00:08:31,810 --> 00:08:34,360
you're just sort of very briefly laying out here's what

170
00:08:34,360 --> 00:08:35,240
we're going to be doing.

171
00:08:35,240 --> 00:08:36,820
Here's why I'm doing it.

172
00:08:36,820 --> 00:08:40,250
So that's kind of what I want you to be thinking about for your informative

173
00:08:40,250 --> 00:08:44,870
introductions, an opening device, a statement of relevance, and an

174
00:08:44,870 --> 00:08:47,830
orientation to the speech itself so we know how you're going to

175
00:08:47,830 --> 00:08:49,530
navigate your time.

176
00:08:49,530 --> 00:08:50,240
All right.

177
00:08:50,240 --> 00:08:50,930
Introductions.

178
00:08:50,930 --> 00:08:52,870
Let's talk a little bit about conclusions.

179
00:08:52,870 --> 00:08:57,340
Conclusions typically are shorter, because this is coming after we've

180
00:08:57,340 --> 00:08:58,920
heard all that information.

181
00:08:58,920 --> 00:09:02,360
So if the introduction is setting us up for it, the conclusion is just sort

182
00:09:02,360 --> 00:09:06,770
of reaffirming it and giving us a nice thought to go out on.

183
00:09:06,770 --> 00:09:10,580
So in terms of your review, well, I think that--

184
00:09:10,580 --> 00:09:13,690
so again in your conclusion you should probably review your key points and

185
00:09:13,690 --> 00:09:15,450
then end on a concluding device.

186
00:09:15,450 --> 00:09:19,010
So in that review, once again you're just hitting those key ideas.

187
00:09:19,010 --> 00:09:23,530
Whatever you said your preview, you're probably saying again in your review.

188
00:09:23,530 --> 00:09:25,140
You're not redoing the whole speech.

189
00:09:25,140 --> 00:09:26,140
That's gone.

190
00:09:26,140 --> 00:09:29,200
You're just hitting the key themes, reaffirming what

191
00:09:29,200 --> 00:09:30,550
those key themes were.

192
00:09:30,550 --> 00:09:34,180
If somebody left your speech and somebody said, well, what was the

193
00:09:34,180 --> 00:09:35,060
speech about?

194
00:09:35,060 --> 00:09:37,040
Oh, it was about three things.

195
00:09:37,040 --> 00:09:39,800
You told us what those three things were at the preview.

196
00:09:39,800 --> 00:09:43,950
And you reminded what those three things were in the review.

197
00:09:43,950 --> 00:09:47,400
So it's just a way of reinforcing those key ideas.

198
00:09:47,400 --> 00:09:50,720
And it also provides a strategic function, because it's starting to

199
00:09:50,720 --> 00:09:53,310
signal to your audience that you're about to be done.

200
00:09:53,310 --> 00:09:54,270
You're not done yet.

201
00:09:54,270 --> 00:09:55,470
But you're about to finish.

202
00:09:55,470 --> 00:09:56,480
And that's also good.

203
00:09:56,480 --> 00:10:01,290
It's sort of helping us adjust our expectations.

204
00:10:01,290 --> 00:10:04,050
And then you get into sort of that final line or those

205
00:10:04,050 --> 00:10:05,440
final couple of lines.

206
00:10:05,440 --> 00:10:09,390
Well, in an informative speech, you can certainly plan these out more

207
00:10:09,390 --> 00:10:09,970
deliberately.

208
00:10:09,970 --> 00:10:11,280
And that's a good thing.

209
00:10:11,280 --> 00:10:15,870
So after you've reminded us of the topic's importance, you've got these

210
00:10:15,870 --> 00:10:20,260
couple of lines that you can just use to sort of put the final capper on

211
00:10:20,260 --> 00:10:21,240
your speech.

212
00:10:21,240 --> 00:10:25,890
One thing that can help, or one thing that's kind of nice to do, is whatever

213
00:10:25,890 --> 00:10:29,010
you started out with at the beginning of the speech, maybe now you pick up

214
00:10:29,010 --> 00:10:30,740
again in the concluding device.

215
00:10:30,740 --> 00:10:35,160
So you started off with a discussion of washing machines, end with a

216
00:10:35,160 --> 00:10:36,690
discussion of washing machines.

217
00:10:36,690 --> 00:10:40,010
In that speech I mentioned, where we started with that story of the child

218
00:10:40,010 --> 00:10:42,695
who died, well, we certainly ended with that.

219
00:10:42,695 --> 00:10:47,690
That was a real solid concluding note that reaffirmed the topic's importance

220
00:10:47,690 --> 00:10:49,990
but also tied back to the conclusion.

221
00:10:49,990 --> 00:10:53,890
So we got a real nice alpha, omega thing going on with our speech here.

222
00:10:53,890 --> 00:10:56,750
It shows sort of deliberate attention to its arrangement.

223
00:10:56,750 --> 00:10:59,310
And it sounds like you're done.

224
00:10:59,310 --> 00:11:04,470
So as you're working through your informative speech, by now you should

225
00:11:04,470 --> 00:11:06,280
have a fully functional draft.

226
00:11:06,280 --> 00:11:09,960
That's really where my concern is, making sure you've got your key ideas

227
00:11:09,960 --> 00:11:13,110
in their proper order and you're knowing how you're working through it.

228
00:11:13,110 --> 00:11:16,140
Introductions and conclusions should come last, because it's trying to

229
00:11:16,140 --> 00:11:20,590
figure out, as novices to this information, how we need to be walked

230
00:11:20,590 --> 00:11:23,930
into this material and then how we can leave this material.

231
00:11:23,930 --> 00:11:26,100
That's what introductions and conclusions do.

232
00:11:26,100 --> 00:11:30,480
They're strategic in their design, certainly for informative speeches.

233
00:11:30,480 --> 00:11:34,970
When we get into eulogies or something like that, introductions and

234
00:11:34,970 --> 00:11:36,890
conclusions are performing different roles.

235
00:11:36,890 --> 00:11:40,590
But here, they're helping us navigate our time with the speaker

236
00:11:40,590 --> 00:11:41,660
and with the audience.

237
00:11:41,660 --> 00:11:46,470
So those introductions should quickly grab our attention, get us interested

238
00:11:46,470 --> 00:11:49,940
in the topic, orient us to how you're going to spend your time.

239
00:11:49,940 --> 00:11:50,930
We hear your speech.

240
00:11:50,930 --> 00:11:54,040
And then at the end, we're reminded of what those key ideas are.

241
00:11:54,040 --> 00:11:57,530
And you send us off with a nice concluding note.

242
00:11:57,530 --> 00:12:01,860
So with that, we'll end our discussion of introductions and conclusions.

